         <abstract>
            <p>The required growth factor measures the amount of future (real) growth that will justify a firm's stock price. Is the company expected to become twice as large as it is today, three times as large, or more? The required growth factor is a concrete measure of growth an investor or student can compare to the size of a firm's potential markets. If the required amount of growth is larger than the firm's potential markets, the firm's stock price is too high. The required growth factor is illustrated for three firms—Microsofi, Wal-Mart, and K-Mart—using data from the 1989 to 2000 period.</p>
         </abstract>
